'''Edwin "Ted" Coubray''' (19 October 1900 &ndash; 10 December 1997) was a New Zealand projectionist, film-maker and inventor. He was born in [[Eastern Bush]], [[Southland Region|Southland]], [[New Zealand]], and died in Homebush, [[Sydney]].<ref name="DNZB Coubray">{{DNZB|title=Edwin Coubray|first= Diane|last= Pivac|id=5c38|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> He retired to Australia in 1973 after ''Auckland Cinemas'' for which he was working closed the Tudor Cinema, [[Remuera]].

He directed and produced [[Carbine's Heritage]] (1927); and was involved as cameraman, photography  or continuous printer in [[The Birth of New Zealand]] (1922), [[Rewi's Last Stand (1925)|Rewi's Last Stand]] (1925),  [[The Adventures of Algy]] (1925), [[The Romance of Maoriland]] (1930), [[Hei Tiki]] (1935) (although he was fired by the eccentric producer [[Alexander Markey]], who also sold his camera to his rivals, the Welsh brothers), and [[Rewi's Last Stand (1940)|Rewi's Last Stand]] (1940). In 1929 he presented New Zealand's first newsreel, under the title ''Coubraytone News.''

He built much of his own equipment, and his company was called ''New Zealand Radio Films.''

